{
  "doc_id": "52076",
  "text": "1,2 Aberrant expression of LCN2 has also been noted in human cancers [CITATION_1] including breast, [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] gastric, [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] esophageal, [CITATION_9] renal, [CITATION_10] brain [CITATION_11] and colorectal [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] cancers. Additionally, Lcn2 is upregulated in response to various other stresses in different organs including involution in the breast, [CITATION_14] reperfusion in the kidney [CITATION_15] and colitis. [CITATION_16] Functionally, LCN2 has a number of different activities that may contribute to its oncogenic potential (reviewed in Rodvold et al. [CITATION_17] ). First, LCN2 binds to matrix metalloproteinase (MMP)9 and sustains its activity by reducing the rates of autoproteolysis. [CITATION_18] [CITATION_19] [CITATION_20] For several forms of cancer, the presence of this complex is the key attribute of aberrant LCN2 expression. [CITATION_21] [CITATION_22] [CITATION_23] Second, LCN2 controls iron availability. For this activity, it was first found to bind to bacterial iron siderophores and thus inhibit bacterial iron uptake and growth. [CITATION_24] [CITATION_25] [CITATION_26] [CITATION_27] More recently, candidate mammalian iron siderophore(s) as well as LCN2 receptor(s) suggest that LCN2 may also mediate a host iron-scavenging strategy. [CITATION_28] [CITATION_29] [CITATION_30] [CITATION_31] [CITATION_32] Finally, LCN2 is proposed to have proinflammatory properties that are potentially independent of its other activities. [CITATION_33] [CITATION_34] MMP activity, bacterial exposure and inflammation are all factors that have a role in intestinal tumorigenesis. The mouse intestinal tumor model APCmin (reviewed in Moser et al. [CITATION_35] ) develops intestinal tumors at multiples of 10-120 per mouse and is sensitive to altered host innate immunity, [CITATION_36] the presence of gut microbes [CITATION_37] [CITATION_38] and MMP deficiency, including loss of MMP9. [CITATION_39] [CITATION_40] Here, we examined whether LCN2 has a more general role in tumorigenesis by examining APCmin intestinal tumorigenesis in an LCN2-deficient background. We found that LCN2 affected neither multiplicity nor total tumor sizes in either the small intestines or colon. Surprisingly, LCN2 deficiency increased tumor multiplicity specifically in the duodenum, suggesting a potential tumor-suppressive activity. Concurrently, LCN2 promoted average small intestinal tumor growth in the distal small intestine. We found that this increase was not correlated to immune activities but rather to tumor iron(II) content. In contrast with mammary tumor models, however, LCN2 deficiency gave only a modest effect, suggesting it is not a robust oncogene in intestinal tumorigenesis.",
